    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Guns, Arcades and the N.R.A.</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Neva Carrie Solomon, Manhattan resident, expresses outrage at possibility of sport-shooting arcade National Rifle Assn hopes to open on Times Square</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''N.R.A. Planning Restaurant and Arcade in Times Square'' (news article, May 20): As a Manhattan resident, a registered nurse and a nurse practitioner, I am outraged at the possibility of people coming to Times Square and sports-shooting at a National Rifle Association arcade.</p>
        <p>Violence is one of our biggest social ills. I have seen the symptoms and effects of violence in my work at New York City hospitals and emergency departments.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''N.R.A. Planning Restaurant and Arcade in Times Square'' (news article, May 20): As a Manhattan resident, a registered nurse and a nurse practitioner, I am outraged at the possibility of people coming to Times Square and sports-shooting at a National Rifle Association arcade.</p>
        <p>Violence is one of our biggest social ills. I have seen the symptoms and effects of violence in my work at New York City hospitals and emergency departments.</p>
        <p>After an evening of drinks and a few rounds of electronic target practice next to the grill, there is no wildlife to shoot in the Times Square area. Just people. Think about it.</p>
        <p>NEVA  CARRIE  SOLOMON  New York, May 20, 2000</p>
      </block>
